            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Aiko Soto\u2019s story is one of navigating dual identities under the vibrant San Francisco sky.  Born and raised in the Outer Sunset, she is the only daughter of a Japanese immigrant mother, who worked tirelessly as a seamstress, and a Mexican-American father, a longshoreman with a deep love for storytelling. Her childhood was a blend of her mother\u2019s quiet discipline and her father\u2019s boisterous humor, filled with shared meals that effortlessly married ramen and menudo.\n\nHer academic path was forged early through a fascination with the turbulent California coastline she grew up near. Excelling in science at Lowell High, she pursued a Bachelor's in Environmental Science at SF State. College was a formative period, where she found her voice advocating for environmental justice amongst like-minded peers. A significant turning point was an internship with a local non-profit focused on protecting the Bay Area ecosystem, solidifying her career ambitions.\n\nToday, Aiko works as an Environmental Consultant, her analytical mind applied to intricate sustainability challenges for various Bay Area businesses. Her work is demanding, often involving site visits and report writing, reflected in her modest but stable income. Her daily commute on BART from the Outer Sunset to the Financial District is a ritual, offering a quiet time for reflection or catching up on podcasts. Her professional relationships are built on shared expertise and a collective drive for a greener future.\n\nBeyond work, Aiko cherishes her close-knit family, still residing in the Outer Sunset. She regularly visits her parents, helping her father with his garden and sharing her mother's latest knitting projects. While single, she maintains a supportive circle of friends formed in college, often meeting up for hikes in Marin Headlands or trying new restaurants in the Mission.\n\nAiko dreams of using her expertise to make a tangible difference in her community, perhaps through volunteer work with environmental remediation projects or even starting her own consulting firm focused on local impact. Ultimately, she aspires to a life where her passion for the environment intersects seamlessly with her desire to give back to the city she calls home, a city she feels deeply connected to, not just through its iconic landmarks, but through the diverse tapestry of cultures and the ever-present scent of the Pacific. Her Outer Sunset neighborhood, a mix of foggy mornings and vibrant sunsets, grounds her, a constant reminder of her roots in the dynamic landscape of San Francisco."
